 <p><div align=center><img src="http://kailyainori.freeservers.com/xiansig.jpg"><br>Teehee.</div></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Spanky > You</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/5/02 5:40:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=44>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/spanky.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Go become a medical professional and do it for many years, then come tell me that the vast majority of doctors and other health care professional are apathetic to patients.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I never said they were apathetic.  I said they had God complexes, blamed the patient, railroaded him through (at a couple of clinics, Mayo Jacksonville being the primary one), didn't listen to him, and missed a very obvious diagnosis, but...none of them seemed completely apathetic, no. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Perhaps your fiance was just a complete pain in the ass to every doctor he saw<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, he was generally too out of it to say much at all besides answer their questions.  He was always excited and enthusiastic about each new diagnosis and treatment, since he wanted so badly to find out what he had and get better, but he became disillusioned as more and more didn't work.  It was me who came in sorta late in the process, and after seeing what was happening to him and seeing him being bullied by his current doctor (the one with all the nasty drug combinations), that turned into something of a &quot;pain in the ass.&quot; :P  I did my homework though, and I didn't (and don't) argue with doctors unless it's something I have read extensively about.  And it turns out I *was* right, because we (yeah I have it too, but that's another story) are finally getting better.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Doctors do not just &quot;toss aside&quot; all previous records and information.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hmm some have, and even more than that the administrators of clinics have.  When nascens went through Mayo, most of the doctors he saw had not even seen his previous medical records, and they made him redo all of the expensive (and often painful, one sending him into a seizure -- after he warned them it would and they still didn't take the necessary precautions) tests he had had at least a few times before.  I really fail to see why it is necessary to redo very expensive tests even &quot;a few weeks&quot; after they have been done with negative results.  Why do them at all, if by the time you get the results back they are out of date?  His illness was the same during all the years he was sick.  So were almost all of his symptoms.  And yes, every single time the same tests were done, the results were the same.  <br>
<br>
Money is always an issue, especially if you are too sick to work, and we were treated at that clinic as just another source of money.  In fact, we refused to pay because of the horrible way we were treated, and after a few letters I wrote explaining our protests to the president of Mayo, they called the  collection agencies off and stopped threatening to sue us, realizing we had a pretty damn good case against them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And, sure, you have a few incompetent health care providers out there...somewhere.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Honestly...you are taking this as a personal insult to the medical profession, and it did sound like that from my post, but I'll point out the following.  Maybe I just have competence standards that are too high.<br>
<br>
Throughout grade school, I had 3-4 teachers that I really thought were good, a bunch that were ok, and several that were just horrible.  In college the ratio was better...more that were really good, less that were really horrible.  In EQ even...I know a handful of players that are really good, a bunch that are ok, and...ok well quite a few that really suck too. :P  That's just the way people are, and fields like medicine are the less forgiving ones.  <br>
<br>
Is it too much to ask to be open minded and compassionate to your patient?  That's really all we asked in a doctor, but it was the hardest to find.  We didn't expect them all to know exactly what fibromyalgia is (it is, after all, a pretty newly discovered illness) and recognize it instantly, but when we came to them saying hey this is not working and nascens feels even worse, we hoped they would listen and not yell at him and make him feel even worse.  Or would at least read the studies I brought them, consider that their original diagnosis *might* be wrong, and possibly try the treatment I had brought them research on.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But to label every doctor (regardless if it is the south) as apathetic and incompetent is reckless and slanderous<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That was not done here; go re-read my earlier posts.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And then  trust their opinions. That doesn't mean not ever getting a second opinion, or not asking many questions...but it does mean that at the end of the day you have to believe in the doctor you've chosen.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We did, which is why on nascens' medical record there are at least a dozen diagnoses and even more different treatments tried. :P  It was several years before we became disillusioned enough to try to find the answer ourselves, and stopped &quot;trusting&quot; most of our doctors.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> For every one bad case you hear about there are at least 10 good cases you never hear about<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, my experiences:<br>
<br>
42ish doctors, several at clinics.  4 compassionate ones that listened to us and were open minded, 3 of which admitted that they could not help him but wished us luck finding out what was really wrong (and no, that wasn't what we &quot;wanted to hear&quot; :P).  5-10 who actually knew what fibromyalgia is (and no, it's not rare).  5-6 that actually yelled at nascens because he questioned their diagnosis and/or the treatment was not working and &quot;it must be his fault.&quot;  20 or so gave him diagnoses that they were &quot;absolutely positive&quot; of, all turned out to be wrong.  1 gave him a very dangerous combination of medicines, one that had a huge warning label saying NOT to prescribe that for the condition the doctor had just diagnosed him with -- thank god he didn't really have that condition (but he's head of his department -- can we really take that to the medical board?).  And almost all repeated expensive tests that he had had done sometimes several times before.<br>
<br>
So, either we're really really unlucky, or out of our rather large sampling maybe 1 in 10 doctors are &quot;good&quot; ones.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> But when people say EVERY medical person out there is greedy and doesn't give a rat's ass about patients<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Once again, that's not being said here. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I brought people back from the dead, and it doesn't even matter to the vast general public<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sure it does.  You did your job (and hopefully did it well), good for you. The garbage man came to get my garbage and recycling today, and did a good job of it, and boy was I glad of that too!  I used to teach little girls dancing and fix computers, those were my jobs, and I thought I did a decent job of those.  Let's not get into the &quot;you should respect me because my job is more important than yours&quot; debate, please.  That's probably the main thing that gives doctors their &quot;God Complexes.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  To the select few of you who have *always* had bad run-ins with every person who has tried to treat you, I suggest this - just stop going for help. You are obviously wasting your money, as most of you say nobody is doing a damn thing for you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
/shrug -- I'm pleased as punch with my current doctor, love him to death.  He's a 70 year old man with so much energy it makes me tired watching him, and he's got my illness too (under control, though). :P  On his treatment I went from narcotic pain medicines to not even advil, from lying in bed delirious to...er...sitting in front of a computer. :P  Ok I'm not quite there yet, but I'm getting there!  Nascens is also loads better too, just takes forever. <p><center><a href="http://www.theroyalknights.org" alt="Adjani Tristesse, Saucy Kitty of TRK"><img src="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/adjsig14.jpg"></a>
<br>Saucy Kitty of
<a href="http://www.theroyalknights.org">The Royal Knights</a>
 </center>

</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/utarotoflanys.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TarotofLanys</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://dr.drakeramoray.50megs.com/10x10/3leafclover.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><FONT COLOR=AA0000><B>Moderator Pirate</B></FONT></span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/5/02 8:53:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=45>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://eqscreenshot.homestead.com/files/EvilTarot.JPG width=94 height=186></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> God Tarot, I'm sorry, but that phrase bugs the living shit out of me. It's that exact mentality that is the problem - the sense of entitlement, the sense that doctors work for you or owe you something.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm paraphrasing Nek's post, go back and read it for a full jist of what he said, it was a good post.<br>
<br>
However, I'm going to absolutely disagree with you here. Patients SHOULD have a sense of entitlement. Doctors work <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> for</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> their patients, not just with them. And while it seems semantical, it is exactly that appearance of arrogance that causes so many patients to distrust doctors.<br>
<br>
The distinction IMO is important, because far too many patients completely hand over everything to a physician. And that's dangerous. And yes, since my husband works medical board cases, I am biased. I've seen the direct results of that.<br>
<br>
I'm not talking about patients who continually refuse to follow medical advice, about changing habits and lifestyles, and then blaming the doctor when they have to have a triple bypass. Or patients who continually refuse to follow a correct course of treatment.<br>
<br>
However, all too many patients blindly and willingly follow a doctor to the point of sacrificing their health for it. <br>
<br>
Most people posting, are offering first hand experiences with shitty doctors. Does that mean all doctors are horrible? No. Do I think you're a horrible arrogant doctor? No. Actually Nek based on what little interaction I've had with you, and what I've read of your posts that I can recall, I think you're probably a damn fine person who cares.<br>
<br>
Let's run down briefly my shit experiences with doctors. Just mine, in my 30 years of life.<br>
<br>
When I was about 12, I broke my ankle. It was a hairline fracture. Rather than putting on a cast, a doctor who had been working an extremely long shift, who wanted to go home said &quot;fuck it&quot; and ace-bandaged it. The nurse argued with him, and was vetoed. I heard the entire conversation while extremely doped up on codeine. I related it later to my parents who were sure I must have misheard. I have had numerous injuries to that same ankle over the years and it is &quot;weak&quot;. Often when running, the ankle would give out and twist. I had so many sprains to that ankle that I don't bother to even seek medical treatment for it anymore.<br>
<br>
When I was in my 20s I stopped menstrating normally. I went to 3 or 4 ob/gyns who told me a variety of bullshit from &quot;Not every woman will menstrate&quot; to &quot;well as you get older...&quot; Finally I went to a specialist who my mother had seen, and who is a wonderful doctor, who correctly diagnosed PCOD. Which is also the cause of my infertility. However at least 3 previous ob/gyns <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> couldn't even be bothered to run the basic blood tests for this</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> because I was not overweight, and I did not have abnormal body hair, two symptoms of the syndrome.<br>
<br>
When I was 26, I lost half the vision in my left eye. We went to the ER because my husband, who has medical training, and was pre-med and works for the medical board, thought I might have an inter-cranial bleed. The doctor I saw at the ER ran no tests, he wiggled his fingers in front of my eyes, proclaimed he thought it was a detached retina, and said he did not have the equipment there to make a full diagnosis. (Which was untrue, the ER has the equipment as we found out later). That I was to see opthamology the next day, and to go home and not bounce around too much.<br>
<br>
When I went to opthamology, they were <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> horrified</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. Had it been a detached or detaching retina, I would be blind in that eye due to his gross negligence. Fortunately it was not that, I was diagnosed with psuedotumor cerebri after several tests.<br>
<br>
When I was diagnosed with PTC, I was put on diamox, which is the first dieretic of choice for that. Unfortunately I had every single side-effect in the worst possible way. I was violently ill. I was told there was no other medication. <br>
<br>
We switched neurologists. I was vomiting constantly, could not engage in any activity for more than 15-20 minutes without being so fatigued I would sleep for hours. I was in constant pain between the head pain, and the pins and needles in my hands and feet. Even walking was agony. Food when I could eat tasted horrible. It was literally hell.<br>
<br>
There are numerous other medications. There was no reason for me to be on that one. Especially due to the side effects. When I demanded of the new neurologist why this other doctor would have told me there was <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> no other medication</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> it was justified as &quot;Well what you have is uncommon. He probably simply didn't know&quot;. That was seen as a reasonable excuse.<br>
<br>
This new neurologist, who I actually like, also was adamant on shunting me as a &quot;cure&quot;. However I took it upon myself to not only educate myself on this illness, but also seek outside expert opinions. Fortunately we have many friends who are doctors and experts in various fields. The neurologist was not fully disclosing the risks and disadvantages of such a procedure. When I asked him about this, he admitted there were problems, but wanted to proceed, because he saw it as a quick fix. (He literally said that). <br>
<br>
Not a month later this same neurologist, despite continuing symptomology wanted to remove me from the dieretics. After my husband (loudly) protested that I was still having visual disturbances, still having symptoms of edema, still having severe head pain, he consulted my chart. And then tried to press once more for surgery <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> when not 5 minutes before he was ready to remove me from all medication and pronounce it resolved!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I'm leaving out the numerous doctors who simply gave me medication for asthma, as I went to the ER approximately every 6 weeks for almost 2 years, because they all assumed I had asthma since a child <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> because they couldn't be bothered to read my chart</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and NO ONE thought to tell me how to manage it. It took two years of battling with doctors before one realized &quot;Oh my God, you developed asthma as an adult, do you do this, do you do that?&quot; and they were HORRIFIED at the fact that this had gone on for so long. I told them that one doctor said I had it, and the rest just dumped medication on me, rescue inhalors and tried to get me to take predisone. <br>
<br>
 I went for a full allergy screening (no allergies) and was given a pneumonia vaccination because I had chronic pneumonia at that point.<br>
<br>
After the vaccination, my asthma improved 99%. They assume now I probably had chronic pneumonia that was causing the asthma. I use a rescue inhalor now <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> maybe</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 10 times a year, if that. They also finally authorized a $200 machine to give me a mist of medication...which is basically what I was going to the ER for every damned month. And a session with a nurse to explain asthma; treatment and management.<br>
<br>
Realize also that the asthma and PTC occurred while I was with my husband. Even between us, who are obviously not ignorant of this field...look what occurred.<br>
<br>
Is this to say all doctors are shit? No. It is to say that people need to take control of their health. Whether that's by a willingness to manage their own health care, by following doctor's advice, or by educating themselves on what's wrong with them, and questioning the doctors until they understand.<br>
<br>
Even with the fertility issues, the first ob/gyn I went to, whom I liked and still like as a doctor, attempted to dismiss PCOD. Fortunately I had been through that before and knew why. And he was able to listen as I explained my history. I was forwarded to a department head, who ran all the tests. Not everything was conclusive, but he was smart enough also to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> listen</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to what we were telling him, and look at previous tests and histories. While I don't fit into the absolute pigeonhole of people with this, that's what's wrong. And additional tests confirmed what I knew, which was I was not ovulating due to hormonal deficency. <br>
<br>
Doctors are not <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> gods</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and patients should also understand that as well. They are people who are attempting to help others, yes. However they can also make mistakes that have a serious impact on people's lives. Which is why I personally believe it is absolutely essential for people to take ownership of their own health, and recognize that a doctor works for them. And if they are not happy with those services they should find another physician. That is not a license to 'shop around until you hear what you want to hear', because that is purely stupid.<br>
<br>
However it important that they take care and consideration in choose a physician. And that they are personally involved in their own health care. And that they have a doctor that they are not only confident in, but who also is willing to take the time to make sure that they understand what is going on, who will answer their questions, listen to them, and explain whatever processes are occurring and viable alternatives.<br>
<br>
Yes, doctors should work with their patients, however patients should not lose sight of the fact that the doctors work for them. They are not doing you a favor by treating you. They are paid professionals providing a valuable service for a fee. That doesn't mean that they cannot care, or do not care. I know for a fact they do.<br>
<br>
I'm leaving out the good stories...the doctors who worked on me for 3 hours in surgery when I had what the department head of anthesia described as the worst asthma attack he had ever seen in his 25 year career, on the table. They worked 3 hours to bring me safely out of anthesia. He also looked in on me every hour after admittance long after he should have gone home, because he was so concerned for me. He didn't <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> have</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to do that. But he did. And when I had to have a second surgery, he completely changed his schedule to make sure he was my attending anesthesiologist  <br>
again, because he was there before. And he went with an alternative to sedation, by using an epidural, and other drugs to make me comfortable, and blissfully have no memory of it as well hehe. And he has it noted and also told me *any* time I have to have surgery if possible to please notify him, and he will make every effort to be there, and if not he will talk with the doctors involved to make them completely aware of what to potentially expect. Even though my chances of that occurring again are only 20%. <br>
<br>
My current ob/gyn has designated on my chart that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> no one</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> but he is to treat me for the infertility, even though policy is that people going through the infertility treatments are supposed to see anyone available in the doctor pool for that. He will also be my ob/gyn for pregnancy because of the other health issues. He doesn't have to do that, his schedule is precious since he works as a department head, and primarily only on high risk cases. However he <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>cares</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> and since he is familiar with everything wants to be the only doctor handling it.<br>
<br>
Unfortuantly I'm a patient some doctors loathe. I have reactions to things I shouldn't, and no bad reactions to things I should. I don't fit into many typical archatypes. I shouldn't have had that severe problem in surgery, but my recovery was nothing short of astounding. I should have had perm. vision loss from the optic nerve damage due to the severely increased cerebral fluid levels...yet my vision returned 100%. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I've had more than one doctor introduced to me because PTC is so rare that they may never see a case in their career. And I've been asked if I mind them doing a full exam, and neurological exam for their benefit. I don't mind one iota. They care enough to want to educate themselves on what to look for. They ask many questions so if they come upon it during their career they can identify it. I'm more than willing to be poked and prodded for that. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I'm not bashing on doctors, I would venture to say even with my poor experiences <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> most</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> doctors care deeply about their patients and are there to help them. However they're not perfect. The one thing that is continious in patient care is the patient. They *must* be involved in their care. And they must have a physician with whom they can do that. And if not, then they need to recognize the fact that the doctor when all is said and done, works for them, and fire them and find another physician.<br>
