<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I never said they were apathetic. I said they had God complexes, blamed the patient, railroaded him through (at a couple of clinics, Mayo Jacksonville being the primary one), didn't listen to him, and missed a very obvious diagnosis<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> I can't see how the diagnosis was obvious and the tests were done it was missed... you have what is called a diagnosis of exclusion.   There is much controversy whether or not the disease even truly exists.  This isn't an 'obvious diagnosis'.  I know in chronic pain and fatigue, you look for -every physical cause- possible before moving to &quot;chronic fatigue syndrome' or 'fibromyalgia'<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> nascens went through Mayo, most of the doctors he saw had not even seen his previous medical records, and they made him redo all of the expensive (and often painful, one sending him into a seizure -- after he warned them it would and they still didn't take the necessary precautions) tests he had had at least a few times before. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Actually redoing tests is standard if the clinic doing so only trusts its own results.  I've ordered repeat CTs (very expensive if uninsured) simply because other centers have different protocols.  MRIs, same thing.  LPs, blood cultures, xrays even... often they are re-done.  Again, you mention a painful test that sent him into a seizure, yet they didn't take precautions?  It just doesn't make sense.  Having done nearly every test known to man, you spend a few minutes ensuring all your bases are covered, to -not- is malpractice.<br>
<br>
And I'm not sure what test for fibromyalgia will cause seizures, could you be more specific?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Or would at least read the studies I brought them, consider that their original diagnosis *might* be wrong, and possibly try the treatment I had brought them research on<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  I guarantee anyone dealing with chronic pain has read the studies.  We all have.  Promise on that one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 5-10 who actually knew what fibromyalgia is (and no, it's not rare)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->.  Um.  err.  U sure about that?  It's been a hot topic for over 20 years.  I'd be hardpressed to find 5-10 doctors in NA who don't know what it is.  Understanding it... that's another issue.  Becuase honestly, it's a patient-reported disease.  No test shows it, no treatment guarantees coverages, no test excludes it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1 gave him a very dangerous combination of medicines, one that had a huge warning label saying NOT to prescribe that for the condition the doctor had just diagnosed him with -- thank god he didn't really have that condition (but he's head of his department -- can we really take that to the medical board?). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Please name the medications, I'd like to know what they were doing that was so terrible... it sounds horrible if its a stark Contraindication, and yes, you could take him to the medical board.  Even the head of the department needs to be licensed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> probably the main thing that gives doctors their &quot;God Complexes.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  Some doctors have God Complexes, no doubt.  But a lot of patients have an inferiority complex (that is, they have an automatic assigning of traits to education and standing in society), so that any display of personality is -projected onto the doctor- as being superior and high-handed.  I'm not saying that's the case with you, but its often the case.  <br>
<br>
Fact is, doctors usually occupy the 'top social rung' of the ladder... due to salary and just society's assigning of doctors to that place... and anyone on that rung will be a little much sometimes.  But at the same time, everone 'below' will be assigning a lot of attributes to people above them.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> On his treatment I went from narcotic pain medicines to not even advil, from lying in bed delirious to...er...sitting in front of a computer. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Which treatment worked for you?  I'm curious as fibromyalgia is such a tricky disease.<br>
<br>
Certain groups feel its purely psychiatric... a somitization disorder (which is why SSRIs, Gabapentin, etc, tend to work) where psychiatric illness manifests itself as an undiagnosible pain.  Other groups feel its neurologic, irritation or inflammation of nerves, which is why steroids can maybe work.<br>
<br>
Honestly, its a crapshoot.  When i read that you and nascens had fibromyalgia, i knew what type of ordeal both you and the medical staffs went through.  Everyone with fibromyalgia has gone through your path, so frustrated that the medical system 'misses' their diagnosis, but completely non-understanding of how diagnosis works, and how things that are -much more severe- have to be completely excluded before moving into the area of CFS/FM.<br>
<br>
At the same time, when you tell me doctors were yelling at you and nascens, it tells me there is more to the story.  I'm sure things got tense, but remember part of that is on your side.  I'm pretty confident you weren't just sitting there as a doctor berated you, i'm sure you were involved.<br>
<br>
I will also make a generalization, this does not apply to you, but is one of the frustrating things of medicine and being a doctor.  When you have people with chronic conditions, you see the worst in their personality.  Stress and pain and fatigue all contribute to a real change in personality, and as such, patients often arent on their 'best behavior'.  On top of this, there is the doctor-centered frustration of not knowing what's going on.  On top of that, there is a -demand- and -expectation- on the patient that they will be cured as quickly as possible.<br>
<br>
Fibromyalgia, CFS, etc.  its' the suck.  i have sympathy for you and nascens, but i also have sympathy for your healthcare providers.<br>
<br>
xianmonkie<br>
 <p><div align=center><img src="http://kailyainori.freeservers.com/xiansig.jpg"><br>Teehee.</div></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Spanky > You</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/6/02 4:26:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=47>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/spanky.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> Gah, so many misconceptions in the medical field about this illness!!!  *tears hair out* :P<br>
<br>
****begin section on the gory details of fibromyalgia here.  Skip down to below this section if you don't care****<br>
<br>
Fallacy #1: It's an illness under debate, and nobody knows if it really exists.<br>
<br>
Wrong.  It's been recognized by the CDC, AMA, WHO etc. etc. for 10-20 years now.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #2: It might be purely psychological.<br>
<br>
Wrong again.  As it was recognized by the CDC, AMA, etc. etc. it is a physical disorder, not mental what-so-ever (although it affects the brain as well as every other bodily function).<br>
<br>
Fallacy #3: It's a disease of exclusion, which can only be diagnosed after everything else has been ruled out.<br>
<br>
There are definite physical criteria for diagnosis, as accepted by the above organizations and more, and have been for, again, 10-20 years.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #4: Nobody knows what causes it and there is no cure at all.<br>
<br>
Well, I think this one is wrong, as do a whole lot of other FMS sufferers and doctors, but of course not everyone is going to agree here.  After studying every theory and treatment I could find on the disease, I came across the research of a certain UCLA doctor who has FMS himself.  He thinks it is a genetic kidney disorder, that his research proves it (and it was more well supported and conclusive than any other research I could find), and that his treatment corrects it, much like gout treatment corrects gout (same treatment, actually).  It's all very fascinating if you are interested in that sort of stuff, and you can read it, if you are interested, on his website:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.fibromyalgiatreatment.com">www.fibromyalgiatreatment.com</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
We've tried many different treatments, but this is the one that seemed to make the difference for us, and so this is the one we have stuck with through the better part of 4 years.  And, as I mentioned earlier, the results are better than any doctor's prognosis for us originally.  They all said &quot;well there's no cause known and no cure, but if you exercise and take all this medicine for symptoms, maybe you can get a job and lead a somewhat normal life someday.&quot;<br>
<br>
Fallacy #5: Most doctors learned about this in Med school, or at least have read a lot of the research and/or debates about it.<br>
<br>
Of the young doctors I have talked to (old ones went through med school, of course, when nobody knew about FMS), the most anyone mentioned hearing about it in school was a day spent on it in some class covering many different &quot;rare&quot; illnesses.  More than one said they recalled hearing it mentioned one day in class, but not elaborated on.<br>
<br>
Many had heard of it in passing or through literature (although it was shocking how many doctors I went to that read no medical literature whatsoever besides what the pharmaceutical companies sent), but of those the vast majority had a totally wrong impression of what it was and couldn't begin to tell you how to diagnose it.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #7: Adjani can count.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #8: It's rare.<br>
<br>
It is not rare, but causes an enormous amount of mis-diagnoses, mostly because of the misconceptions about it in the medical field I guess.  Also the fact that its symptoms can emulate most every disorder known to man (although having them all together, of course, should set off alarms).  I've read a few studies trying to ascertain how common it really is, and the conclusions were that around 5% of the *total* population have the gene.  Now, to develop the actual illness one usually has to go through a trauma of some sort...car accident, illness, stress, etc.  So a lot of those are &quot;undeveloped,&quot; but then again a lot of them are developed and misdiagnosed, the person just doesn't seek treatment (thinks they are just getting old or whatever), etc.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #9: Guys don't get it.<br>
<br>
It's true that the majority of peeps diagnosed with FMS are women, but guys definitely do get it too.<br>
<br>
Fallacy #10: It's not serious and not fatal.<br>
<br>
There are all sorts of degrees of FMS, so if you know someone who &quot;has it and lives a normal healthy life,&quot; don't assume it's not very serious indeed for others.  My dad, for instance (from whose side of the family I got the gene), displays minor symptoms of it but they barely affect his life at all.  My cousin, however, has had health problems all her life, been diagnosed with all sorts of crap, has been in and out of school (never graduated from high school), and for the most part of her life has been too sick to pass or sometimes even attend her classes at any given time.<br>
<br>
For a great many people, it's completely debilitating.  Some have to use a wheelchair, some can't even get out of bed (I went through a period where I could barely get out of bed).  Most can't work or go to school, some can't leave their houses at all.  These are generally the ones who are too scared/socially anxious/broke/fed up/or just too debilitated to even go to a doctor for it, and just live as invalids.  It's not technically fatal, meaning you can't die from the actual fibromyalgia, but there are a *lot* of things it makes you more susceptible to that greatly increase the risk of death...much like AIDS.  <br>
<br>
Rampant among FMS sufferers is suicide...especially the ones who get told &quot;it's all in your head,&quot; &quot;if you really wanted to get better you could,&quot; &quot;you're just making this up to be lazy,&quot; &quot;your illness doesn't really exist,&quot; &quot;there is no cure and you will be like this for the rest of your life,&quot; etc. etc.  You're right Tarot, so many patients believe everything their doctors tell them...and if you were faced with a life of total dependance and debilitation, with no hope of getting well, how thrilled would you be with the prospect of the rest of your life?  Thank god I didn't take the first few doctors' words for it myself.<br>
<br>
<br>
****end section on the gory details of fibromyalgia****<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I can't see how the diagnosis was obvious and the tests were done it was missed<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The tests they did were not for fibromyalgia...out of the first 40 of those doctors nascens saw, only one even *mentioned* fibromyalgia, and that was to say that he knew little about it but was sure nascens didn't have it.  Fortunately, we picked up a brochure on it on the way out (we were following every potential lead at this point), saw that it *exactly* matched his symptoms and medical history, and from there everything went uphill.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Actually redoing tests is standard if the clinic doing so only trusts its own results.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, I found out that it's standard. :P  Whether it's necessary or not...I'm still not convinced.  Seems awfully greedy to me, perhaps it's a good measure to be &quot;extra special sure&quot; that the tests are done right, but clinics should at least ask the patients if they can afford to have them redone first.  We couldn't, and we didn't expect to be ordered to have them redone.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> And I'm not sure what test for fibromyalgia will cause seizures, could you be more specific?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Like I said, they were *not* testing him for FMS.  They were just running some standard tests, and this particular one required an inordinate amount of blood to be taken from him for analysis.  He warned them that he had gone into a minor seizure the last time he had this done, and that he needed to be lying down on a table and...er something else that I forget.  They said &quot;nah, you'll be fine,&quot; and proceeded to take the blood with him sitting up.  He went into a massive, scary seizure.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I guarantee anyone dealing with chronic pain has read the studies. We all have. Promise on that one<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What studies?  The ones that say chronic pain is all in the head and patients just make it up?  Because that's what I was told by several doctors. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :/ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":/"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> No test shows it, no treatment guarantees coverages, no test excludes it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Physical diagnostic criteria for FMS:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.pendulum.org/related/FMS/COPENHAGEN_DECLARATION.HTM">www.pendulum.org/related/...RATION.HTM</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.sover.net/~devstar/tpdef.htm">www.sover.net/~devstar/tpdef.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
(but yes, they do recommend ruling out a few other conditions that mimic it first)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Please name the medications, I'd like to know what they were doing that was so terrible<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nascens really doesn't want me to post all the meds he's been on here, but if you want I can email them to you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Which treatment worked for you? I'm curious as fibromyalgia is such a tricky disease.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
See link above in the &quot;gory details&quot; section. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Certain groups feel its purely psychiatric<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If it is, it's interesting that I denied forcefully that I was sick until I was so sick I could not get out of bed.  Also interesting that the shrink I saw for a year and all the meds he put me on did nothing.  Also interesting that I exhibit so many visible physical symptoms.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> a somitization disorder (which is why SSRIs, Gabapentin, etc, tend to work) where psychiatric illness manifests itself as an undiagnosible pain. Other groups feel its neurologic, irritation or inflammation of nerves, which is why steroids can maybe work.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Read all those studies...too inconclusive, theories scientifically unsound and not backed up, etc.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> At the same time, when you tell me doctors were yelling at you and nascens, it tells me there is more to the story.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There's not more to the story with the doctor who also gave him the nasty combo of meds.  He yelled at nascens, who had been meek and compliant for so many months, after he had a really bad reaction to multiple meds.<br>
<br>
A doctor at mayo clinic really chewed nascens out because he had a hard time remembering things to answer the guy's questions, and he accused nascens of making things up as he went.  He also yelled at me for helping nascens out with some answers, as my memory was better than his at the time...said I was &quot;obviously controlling him and his problem was that he let me and his mother run his life.&quot;  At that point I stood up for myself and he made me leave the room, lol.  Nascens came out really feeling like sheet after that mental abuse.<br>
<br>
Another doctor we saw, a fibromyalgia doctor, yelled at me mostly.  I was *so* very enthusiastic about him at first, but he just wasn't as much an expert on the treatment we were on as he would like to think (we are seeing the discoverer of the treatment himself now :P).  We stopped getting well for a year and he couldn't figure out why, so he literally told me I was preventing myself from getting well for some reason, and needed to change my outlook or I'd never get better.  Fortunately, our current doctor quickly found out why treatment was not working and got us back on the right track.<br>
<br>
Think this is this long enough yet?  /sigh there's really only 2 topics I can talk about in my current state, EQ and FMS...so I do, and do, and do. :P <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/udarkomen42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DarkOmen42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I had the 15k post on R&R<br>and all I got was this<br>lousy title!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/6/02 5:17:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Seems awfully greedy to me, perhaps it's a good measure to be &quot;extra special sure&quot; that the tests are done right, but clinics should at least ask the patients if they can afford to have them redone first. We couldn't, and we didn't expect to be ordered to have them redone<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
