<br>
it's a diagnosis of exclusion.  let me repeat.  it's a diagnosis of exclusion.  according to the own document provided by you:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Muscle biopsy has revealed important morphological changes but no characteristic ones, and other tests (eg serum levels of muscle enzymes, electromyography, exercise testing and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy ) have not been helpful. Laboratory tests can be important to rule out conditions that mimic fibromyalgia, such as hypothyroidism, polymyalgia rheumatica, or generalized osteoarthritis<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
if you come in with pain, i'm gonna make sure you don't have cancer.  you don't have hypothyroidism.  you don't have RA, you don't have lupus, you don't have a great # of things that are far more likely to kill you.<br>
<br>
from the website you provided (the first one), <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The American Academy of Rheumatology recommends searching for tender points at eighteen predetermined sites on the body. However, individual pain perception varies greatly.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  in other words, you don't even need those 'criteria points' that are mentioned in the Copenhagen Definition to be considered for FMS.  There is no specificity to those points, only mild sensitivity.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Fallacy #1: It's an illness under debate, and nobody knows if it really exists.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Let me clarify.  It's an illness under debate.  Noone can -prove- that it exists in an individual.  You come to me with pain, you could have it, or you could be completely malingering.  There is no way for me to say.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Fallacy #2: It might be purely psychological.  <br>
Wrong again. As it was recognized by the CDC, AMA, etc. etc. it is a physical disorder, not mental what-so-ever (although it affects the brain as well as every other bodily function).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Absoutely not.  There are many psychosomatic disorders that can completely mimic FMS, and more importantly, it is associated highly with psycological disease such as depression, bipolar disorder, and schizophrenia.  I don't know where you got this from, but you're absolutely wrong.<br>
<br>
I stand by my statement, it might be purely psychological.  The mind controls a lot, and we don't know what controls FMS or CFS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There are definite physical criteria for diagnosis, as accepted by the above organizations and more, and have been for, again, 10-20 years<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> No there aren't.  There are clues, but i'm sorry, &gt;80% of the patients i've ever seen with it don't even come close to the Copenhagen definition.  not even close.<br>
<br>
Here's your critera, by your widely cited governing medical bodies : <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There may be local tightness or muscle spasm, although active contractions typically cannot be demonstrated by electromyography. Inflammation only occurs with an underlying systemic condition.<br>
<br>
PFS is recognized by the typical pattern of diffuse fibromyalgia and nonrheumatic symptoms (eg, poor sleep, anxiety, fatigue, irritable bowel symptoms), by exclusion of significant contributory or underlying diseases (eg, generalized osteoarthritis, RA, polymyositis, polymyalgia rheumatica, other connective tissue disease), and by exclusion of psychogenic muscle pain and spasm. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> I took that right from the Merck Manual, which is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> the </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> textbook of diagnosis.<br>
<br>
It's purely a diagnosis of exclusion.  I don't have to have a single 'tender point' to qualify for FM, it just helps.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Many had heard of it in passing or through literature (although it was shocking how many doctors I went to that read no medical literature whatsoever besides what the pharmaceutical companies sent), but of those the vast majority had a totally wrong impression of what it was and couldn't begin to tell you how to diagnose it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  That's because, there is no way to diagnose it.  You put the label on when nothing else fits, and the clinical picture of FM sounds appropriate.  There are no inclusion or exclusion criteria for FM.  Please, if you find some that say 'this is required for the disease' aside from generalized pain, show me.  Cuz i can't find it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Fallacy #7: Adjani can count.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Nothing wrong with unorthodox counting <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> and the conclusions were that around 5% of the *total* population have the gene.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> ERrr gene?  Which gene is that?  There have been no genes found as of yet.  Suggestive of a genetic disorder, but i haven't heard of an isolated FM gene.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Fallacy #9: Guys don't get it.<br>
<br>
It's true that the majority of peeps diagnosed with FMS are women, but guys definitely do get it too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> To be specific, 85% of FM affected people are female.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Yes, I found out that it's standard. :P Whether it's necessary or not...I'm still not convinced. Seems awfully greedy to me<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> In canada, we dont' charge for tests, and we still do it.  It's not greed that motivates retesting.  As to the financial problems of the American patient, I'm not touching that one today <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> They were just running some standard tests, and this particular one required an inordinate amount of blood to be taken from him for analysis.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> How much is inordinate? And what tests? blood tests?  you'd have to take 20 or so vials to do anything remotely damaging.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> What studies? The ones that say chronic pain is all in the head and patients just make it up? Because that's what I was told by several doctors.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> No, the studies that talk about a condition with so many vague symptoms, 0 diagnostic signs, and a strong tendency to occur in females.  No study i've read has convinced me of anything remotely diagnostic for FM.  We had a week of lectures where patients with CFS, FM, etc woudl come in and talk to us.  And we still had no clue about the disease.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If it is, it's interesting that I denied forcefully that I was sick until I was so sick I could not get out of bed. Also interesting that the shrink I saw for a year and all the meds he put me on did nothing. Also interesting that I exhibit so many visible physical symptoms.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> There are many cases of visibly and physically displayable disease that are completely psychological.  There are many people who despite having psychological illness continue to deny they have it.  And there are many people who are completely resistant to psychiatric medications.  Nothing you said would refute a psychiatric diagnosis for pain syndromes.  <br>
<br>
Just because something is psychiatric doesn't mean you're making it up or it's not real.  Schizophrenia is real, and it's purely in the head.  Depression is real, and there is no physical sign for it.  Etc etc.  Only a few old stodgy doctors would say FM isn't real... and just don't go to those ones.<br>
<br>
Any rheumatologist would be more than versed in FM.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> He also yelled at me for helping nascens out with some answers, as my memory was better than his at the time...said I was &quot;obviously controlling him and his problem was that he let me and his mother run his life.&quot; <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  Well were you? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   heehee as a medical interviewer i will say that when you take a history, you want it from the patient.  Often times patients SO's, moms, dads, daughters will pipe in, but i don't want to know them.  I want to know the patient.  Often I'll ask the person to leave, then after talk to them.  I'm certainly not accusing you of anything, but i know that some doctors find it frustrating, already being frustrated with chronic pain issues.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If that's the case, we have a ton of potential lawsuits on our hands. All the tests that were repeated had shown nothing before, and showed nothing again. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> If they missed something like a cancer or a brain/MS type picture, they would be highly negligent.  I'd retest anyone presenting to me with a complicated case like you're describing.  To not is malpractice.  Labs are wrong.  CTs are wrong.  MRIs are wrong.  IT happens all the time.  I treated a patient whos potassium was 7.1 (kinda high), but before i administered the kayexelate (Really nasty stuff) i rechecked, turns out lab error it was 3.5.  Coulda made him actually low.  Lucky there.<br>
<br>
I'll make one more point, one that i don't think the patients with chronic disease understand.<br>
<br>
We get a -lot- of patients who use us to treat their drug addiction, get them off work, send them home from jail, etc etc.  So much so we develop a natural skepticism.  I hope you appreciate this the next time a doctor is hesitant to give pain meds, etc etc.  It's frustrating, especially with something like FMS/CFS that can be completely faked by a patient.  As a doctor you don't want to assume everyone is faking, but you want to start off treating them that way.  Again, malpractice if you didn't.<br>
<br>
xianmonkie<br>
 <p><div align=center><img src="http://kailyainori.freeservers.com/xiansig.jpg"><br>Teehee.</div></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/ualundraadjani.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AlundraAdjani</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Spanky > You</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/6/02 5:51:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=52>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/spanky.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  in other words, you don't even need those 'criteria points' that are mentioned in the Copenhagen Definition to be considered for FMS. There is no specificity to those points, only mild sensitivity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There are actually &quot;lumps&quot; that can be felt there too...deposits of phosphates, as theorized by Dr. St. Amand.  Everyone has a different pain threshold so not all will find them as painful, but the lumps will always be there.  At times the swelling is worse than others, and they are quite large.  I have at least two that are visible with the eye as well as being able to feel them.  But you're right, sometimes poking the points doesn't &quot;hurt,&quot; and so cases can slip through the cracks that way.  But if you do have the lumps and pain at the specific points...chances are very high you have FMS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Noone can -prove- that it exists in an individual. You come to me with pain, you could have it, or you could be completely malingering. There is no way for me to say.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Go read St. Amand's research...he has done physical tests that have shown results in line with his theories.  Also, as I said, I have several visible symptoms.  Some are quite gross, so I'd rather not go into them here :P, but one is rash like bumps all over my arms, legs, and shoulders.  There are others, if you want to know them I can email you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I stand by my statement, it might be purely psychological.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Do you have evidence of that?  Because I have evidence that it is not, and a heck of a lot of it.  Little infuriates me more than to be told this is &quot;all in my head,&quot; as I'm sure you can imagine.  The only doctors that told me it was psychological were also the ones who could not tell me the first thing about its symptoms and how to diagnose it.<br>
<br>
I have never, in all my reading, seen the ties between bipolar disorder and schizophrenia and fibromyalgia.  I have, however, seen the statistics on how often fibromyalgia is misdiagnosed as something else *first* and then later diagnosed as fibromyalgia.  Lots of correlations have been drawn between it and other illnesses simply because of this high incidence of misdiagnoses.  Depression...duh.  Every chronic illness has depression associated with it.  I had my entire life taken away from me and I went from being an overachiever to an invalid.  I'm supposed to be cheerful about it?  Especially when I'm being told that I'm really just making all of it up?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There are clues, but i'm sorry, &gt;80% of the patients i've ever seen with it don't even come close to the Copenhagen definition. not even close.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
How do you know?  Did you watch an experienced FMS doctor poke them?  If this definition weren't used to diagnose them, how were they diagnosed anyhow?  Did the doctor just say...well they don't have anything else, must be fibromyalgia?  If that's the case, perhaps something else *was* overlooked and they don't really have it anyhow.  There are a lot of illnesses that emulate FMS (or a lot of illnesses FMS emulates, however you want to look at it), but none that I have heard of that emulate the exact trigger points of the copenhagen definition.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I took that right from the Merck Manual, which is  the  textbook of diagnosis.<br>
It's purely a diagnosis of exclusion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you go by what's written in your textbook, perhaps.  I'd rather go by the latest research personally, and so would every fibromyalgia specialist I have seen or talked to (admittedly a limited number, but significant that they *all* use this definition for diagnosis).  This isn't something I found and decided to put here to validate myself...this is what is *used* in the field every day.<br>
<br>
I'm sure it's a good thing that you have faith in what is written in your textbooks, but honestly I have found that the &quot;textbook doctors&quot; have been the least help to me.  If it doesn't fit the textbook exactly, they won't do it, or you must be making it up.  It's fine for diagnosing strep throat, or the flu, or whatever...but relatively new and &quot;debated&quot; illnesses, I'd take an open minded well-researched doctor over a valedictorian textbook doctor any day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  ERrr gene? Which gene is that? There have been no genes found as of yet. Suggestive of a genetic disorder, but i haven't heard of an isolated FM gene.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Read the research and studies on the link above...no gene has been isolated, but almost all research shows strong inheritance in the disorder.  My dad has symptoms, my cousin on his side has it, I have it.  Nascens' mother has it (bad), his uncle has symptoms, his brother had it.  Dr. St. Amand's theory, a very interesting one, is that it is a genetic kidney disfunction, and he does have some tests and studies that support the theory.  Not the least of which is that the disease parallels gout very closely, and responds to gout treatment.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  To be specific, 85% of FM affected people are female.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well...85% of FM affected people *as diagnosed by whatever criteria the specific doctor is using,* and according to that particular study are female.  I have no idea what the real percentage is, but I do know that there's a higher suspected percentage of male victims than that -- but doctors are hesitant to diagnose males with it, and males are hesitant to seek diagnosis because of the stigma as purely a female disorder.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  In canada, we dont' charge for tests, and we still do it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In america, many hospitals have been warned or cited for recommending and conducting expensive tests that were not really necessary. :P  LIke the &quot;machine that goes bling&quot; in the miracle of life. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  How much is inordinate? And what tests? blood tests? you'd have to take 20 or so vials to do anything remotely damaging.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We can't remember exactly how much, but I know that they did warn him that it was going to be an awful lot, for a lot of tests.  He warned them that he had to lie down or he would pass out, and they did it with him sitting up anyways.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> We had a week of lectures where patients with CFS, FM, etc woudl come in and talk to us.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A week?  Wow that's a lot more than most doctors I talked to said they got on it in med school...oh yeah, you're in Canada.  Anyhow...there are very many varying symptoms to the disorder, but there's a pretty comprehensive list of about 50 of them.  The many, many other FMS patients I have talked to never had exactly the same case, but they generally had at least 25 or more of the symptoms.  I have about 35 of them, and yes some of them are visible and observable by doctors.  I have found that if you are familiar with the list of symptoms, and the &quot;patterns&quot; they tend to go in (i.e. I had terrible back pain, and that also went along with my nasty calf cramps...I had really bad frontal headaches, and that went along with reactive hypoglycemia...etc.), you have a pretty good idea what the disorder is.  But then of course there's the whole other areas of diagnosing and treating it...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  There are many cases of visibly and physically displayable disease that are completely psychological<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not a doctor, but I wasn't aware you can *make* rash like bumps appear all over your body?  Or make painful lumpy deposits form in particular places (the same places as other FMS patients) on your body?  Or make your face become puffy, break out, and your hair fall out?  Or make your joints swell?  Or make your urine stink (much more so than usual), become cloudy, and often have very high levels of phosphoric acid (yeah I know you can probably do that by eating certain things, but assuming your diet is constant)?<br>
<br>
Well, perhaps not *make* all that happen, but I was not aware a psychological illness could make any of that happen either.  It can do a lot of things that have (visibly) happened to me...like raise stomach acid levels, cause the shaking and anxiety attacks I often get, perhaps even cause the twitching and muscle spasms.  But all the above stuff?  Just seems incredible to me that they could be attributed by *anyone* to psychological causes.  And those are not even remotely rare symptoms of FMS.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Schizophrenia is real, and it's purely in the head.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Schizophrenia doesn't cause those kinds of physical symptoms.  Heck, nothing mental short of what happened in &quot;the exorcist&quot; could, that I have heard of. :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Any rheumatologist would be more than versed in FM.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Making that assumption almost caused us to rule out FMS for nascens (and me) altogether.  We saw a rheumatologist at mayo clinic specifically for the purpose of seeing if he had fibromyalgia.  He said &quot;well I don't know why they sent you to me, since I don't know much about it, but I know it's mainly joint pain and since you don't have joint pain I'm positive we can rule that out.&quot;  His report actually never even made it into our final report or his medical records, though we were charged for the session.  Fortunately we didn't believe him totally, and picked up a brochure on fibromyalgia anyhow.  The brochure -- outside his office -- had a ton more info on fibromyalgia than he seemed to know.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I'm certainly not accusing you of anything, but i know that some doctors find it frustrating, already being frustrated with chronic pain issues.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well...what's more frustrating?  Getting an &quot;I don't know, I don't really remember&quot; to every question you ask, or getting the answer from those who have been around the patient constantly?  That was my reasoning, and there were times when nascens couldn't answer any of his questions due to memory problems.  We wanted to know what he had, we didn't want the doctor's opinion of our personal lives based on a 15 minute interview.<br>
<br>
Also, Nascens' issues were not actually chronic pain, he had many other symptoms but his pain threshold is very high, so pain was a very minor concern for him.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> To not is malpractice. Labs are wrong. CTs are wrong. MRIs are wrong. IT happens all the time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The place where he had the tests done originally was UAB, one of the most respected test centers/medical schools in the south (whether I actually respect them...well, that's another story).  If they are wrong so often, why not schedule 10 tests in a row, just to be sure nothing is missed?  How can you trust just one test no matter where it is?  Could I sue them for malpractice if they only tested me once and it turned out negative, but I really had cancer or something?  /shrug I just don't see where you draw the line at what you trust and what you don't, and maybe the patient should sign a waiver saying that just the previous tests are fine, or just one test is fine, or that he/she requires 100 tests to be absolutely certain.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I treated a patient whos potassium was 7.1 (kinda high), but before i administered the kayexelate (Really nasty stuff) i rechecked, turns out lab error it was 3.5. Coulda made him actually low. Lucky there.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sure, if you turn up *positive* for something you should retest before administering potentially dangerous medications or surgery, nobody would dispute that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  We get a -lot- of patients who use us to treat their drug addiction, get them off work, send them home from jail, etc etc. So much so we develop a natural skepticism. I hope you appreciate this the next time a doctor is hesitant to give pain meds, etc etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, that's very true, and I have faced just such skepticism during the time I had to be on narcotic pain meds just to sleep.  THANK GOD this treatment has &quot;cured&quot; my back pain, so that I am off all pain medications whatsoever, and don't have to put up with the &quot;well why should I give you pain medicine for your back when the x-rays show nothing.  I think you're an addict, and you'll just have to use ibuprofen instead&quot; anymore.  I know doctors have to be very careful, but damn...I have met so many where you come in guilty until proven innocent, unless you have an x-ray or blood test showing something.  They really could at least treat people better until they prove they are a drug addict or are &quot;faking it.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> especially with something like FMS/CFS that can be completely faked by a patient.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, I think there are enough physical symptoms in the average case to observe that it is not being faked.  I'm not saying there are not those out there who fake it and manage to convince doctors, but if you know enough and are observant I think it's easy enough to tell the difference. <p><center><a href="http://www.theroyalknights.org" alt="Adjani Tristesse, Saucy Kitty of TRK"><img src="http://www.theroyalknights.org/sigs/adjsig14.jpg"></a>
