<br>
Anyway, what I was going to say is, I'll talk about PTC instead of fibromyalgia, because that's the one I've been forced to become an expert on.<br>
<br>
PTC is also an illness of exclusion, let's face facts though <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> many</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> illnesses are. The definitive test is when the potential for a brain tumor has been eliminated (by CAT) then if the patient's cerebral spinal fluid pressure is 100-400% of normal, and there is no indiction of brain infection, then it's PTC by exclusion.<br>
<br>
Now, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> most</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> adults with PTC are women. Reason? Unknown. Men do get it, but it's extremely rare. Most people who do not present with perfect symptomology and characteristics go undiagnosed. Many who do, still go undiagnosed for years.<br>
<br>
Most adults with PTC have been in the system for 1-5 years for chronic, severe head pain. Most have been sent for psych. evals. Why? They're told it's all in their head. <br>
<br>
Most are not finally diagnosed until they have perm. vision loss, but have a history of seeing doctors for the head pain for years prior. I'm an exception to that, I never went to the doctors for the head pain. I always had severe headaches, and frankly thought all women did.<br>
<br>
PTC causes headpain more severe than migraines. Some PTC people also have migraines, they say the PTC headpain hands down is more severe. I've had it so bad I've been vomiting, dizzy and can't see straight. Fun shit.<br>
<br>
The <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> only</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> treatment for PTC headpain is narcotics. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NO</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> other medication works. I wish to fuck some other medications did. Migraine medication does not work. Aspirin, does not work. Caffeine does not work. Tylenol, motrin, etc. does not work. Opiates do.<br>
<br>
Now, most doctors apparently do not want to prescribe narcotics for the pain. Most other people I've connected with online who have this, have been refused pain management by their doctors. I haven't had to go through this. I didn't seek treatment for head pain. I had vision loss and so was immediately diagnosed. And from the get-go I've had vicodin for pain management and still have damn near an open 'scipt for it.<br>
<br>
However a majority of people with this are not taken seriously. Their pain is untreated. They're told it's all in their head when an immediate diagnosis cannot be made. They've gone through <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>hell</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->. And eventually end up with perm. vision damage, because they're not properly diagnosed.<br>
<br>
I can understand it. Most doctors have never seen a PTC case. Most doctors I see have never seen it. <br>
<br>
PTC can also be caused by antibiotic reaction, and abuse of vitamins. It can also occur during pregnancy (though if so it almost always resolves immediately after birth) They're more likely to see one of the transition cases. Or a pedatric case. In fact one of the experts we consulted has never seen an adult case, only pedatric cases...which are radically different, and undoubtably have different causation.<br>
<br>
Why does PTC happen? Unknown. Treatments? Only symptomatic treatment. There is no cure. PTC often resolves as mysteriously as it started. I was told it would resolve in 2 years...well it's been over 3 now.<br>
<br>
Do I get pissed about it? Sometimes, but not too often. It's a rare disease, extremely rare. Which is why it can slip through the cracks. And since there are symptomatic treatments, and it doesn't kill people (generally, though I suppose you could die from a burst dura), there's not a ton of research in this area. I can't even argue too much with that. Money for fatal diseases...or just ones that really suck for a few people. Hmmm. <br>
<br>
I am very very fortunate. I have an unbelievably high natural tolerance for pain. I didn't get stuck in the system for headpain. (They still can't believe I never reported the head pain haha prior to severe vision loss). I've never had to fight with a doctor for pain medication. And fortunately I can tolerate most of the pain long enough not to be addicted to the narcotics. Or develop a tolerance. <br>
<br>
However so many people with this haven't had that luxury. Some are legally blind now as a result of going undiagnosed. Many had severe financial or emotional problems as a result of being crippled by the pain and being dumped into psych. because they were told they were malingering...or making it up, or addicts, or it was all in their head, they were nuts.<br>
<br>
Most PTC people I've come into contact with <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> hate</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> doctors as a result of this. Some were in the medical profession themselves as nurses or doctors or the spouse of nurses and doctors. One of the worst cases (she's now blind) was a nurse who went through that shit for 3 years until she went blind. Vision loss can occur rapidly if the warning signs aren't caught. That's the biggest risk of PTC. That and suicide due to chronic severe pain.<br>
<br>
Are there people who are junkies who will lie for a fix? Yah. Are there malingering people, hypochrondrics, and Munchausen Syndrome people out there? Yeap.<br>
<br>
Most people though do not fall into those catagories. However it sure as hell seems most doctors want a 'label' they can slap on someone. I'm personally convinced that most cases of PTC are caused by hormonal problems. I'm absolutely convinced mine is related to a hormonal imbalance. And surprisingly some PTC cases are resolved by carrying a pregnancy to term. (This is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the reason we are trying to have children though.) Most have hormonal problems and a history of menstruate cessasion or difficulties. The longest standing case of PTC...40 years. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Anyway, most people won't go through this type of shit, but you can understand why I can completely sympathize with Adjani. Hell, it wasn't 50 years ago when the parents of schizophrenics were told it was due to shitty parenting. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  When Alzheimer's disease was simply either senility or undiagnosed or misdiagnosed dementia. <br>
<br>
There's quite a bit that's still undetermined by medical science. Even some shit that is, such as PTC, they have no idea of the causes, and therefore haven't a clue on a 'cure'.<br>
<br>
And because so many doctors seem to want to quickly label their 'mystery' cases, if they can't find the cause, then they'll label it psych. or malingering, or whatever else they can pretty much blame on the patient for not being so good as to present their symptoms a little better.  <br>
<br>
Am I damning the medical system? No, I'm actually not. I'm saying it's imperfect. Unfortunately the casualities of that are people. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
