<br>
I'm sorry you had so many bad experiences with doctors, but it seems to me, most of them chose NOT to work with you, instead probably trying to get you out of their office in an expedient manner.  The onus of responsibility lies with the patient - choose your doctors carefully.  That I can agree with you 100%, since I personally see bad doctors around me every day.  Word of caution - some of the most &quot;charming&quot; doctors are the biggest idiots, while some doctors who are crude and vulgar are clinical geniuses.  I'll give you one guess which doctor is more popular with patients and has a busier practice.<br>
<br>
Also realize in this day and age, most doctors are fed up with the system.  You mentioned that you pay doctors for their services.  I defy anyone to tell me the last time they wrote out a check for a doctor.  In truth, you pay an insurance company, or a hospital, for health care.  Most doctors today work for a flat fee, a gauranteed salary.  If they see 10 patients a day or 100 patients, they get paid the same.  Unfortunately, for some doctors this means they have less commitment to a patient, since even if you left, another patient would be right around the corner to fill your spot.<br>
<br>
This is the same reason I laugh when people say surgeons try and operate needlessly for money.  Most surgeons get paid the same whether they operate once a week or 20 times a week - see above.  Every time you operate on someone, there is a chance something will go amok and then you just rewarded yourself with a lifetime of headaches, and open yourself up to liability - who needs that?  So nowadays you will see more surgeons seeking ways NOT to operate rather than operate - isn't socialism a great thing?<br>
<br>
One of my old professors told me that &quot;whenever you want to operate on someone, find out all you can about them, and then decide if this is someone you would want to marry...because once you operate them, they are yours for life.&quot;  I think patients need to apply this same adage when they choose a doctor.  <br>
<br>
Also remember a doctor can only see so many patients in one day, can only operate on &quot;x&quot; number of patients a week.....so why would a doctor ever want to fill their office with difficult, noncooperative, unappreciative, or demanding patients?  In reality, doctors tend to cherry-pick patients as much as patients select doctors, as much as their specialty allows.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
